 :tx/rationale "DOG-FOOD INSIGHT: The API-as-prompt principle reveals a HIERARCHY OF PROMPT SURFACES in braid, ordered by frequency of agent interaction and impact on agent reasoning: (1) GUIDANCE FOOTER — injected into EVERY tool response. Highest frequency, lowest token count. This is AMBIENT activation — shapes the trajectory without consuming k*. Currently works well (M(t) + next action). (2) TASK TITLES — read every time agent picks work. High frequency, should be L1 activation patterns. Currently BROKEN (truncated, mixed content). (3) SEED CONTEXT — read once at session start. Medium frequency, highest token count. Currently GOOD (braid seed assembles relevant context). (4) STATUS DASHBOARD — read periodically for orientation. Medium frequency, medium tokens. Currently OK but missing topology. (5) COMMAND OUTPUT — read per invocation. Low frequency per command, high variety. The biggest gap: NOT ALL OUTPUTS USE SPEC-LANGUAGE. Most just dump data. (6) HELP TEXT — read when agent is confused. Lowest frequency, highest impact when invoked. Currently CONSTRAINT-BASED (flag lists), should be DEMONSTRATION-BASED. (7) ERROR MESSAGES — read on failure. Low frequency, CRITICAL impact. Currently MISSING recovery actions for most errors. The OPTIMIZATION ORDER follows from frequency * impact: fix task titles (2) first, then error messages (7), then command output (5), then help text (6), then status (4). Guidance footer (1) and seed (3) are already good."
